[[div class="lines"]]
[[=]]
+ The Lines Are Down

++ An Oral History of the End of the World
+++ (Abridged Edition)

----

++ Part One: Manifest Destiny
[[/=]]

On September 9, 2002, the SCP Foundation faced an unprecedented crisis: the loss of its insurance coverage.

One month prior, on the tenth of August, Goldbaker-Reinz Insurance Group Ltd. served notice that they would terminate the Foundation's full policy portfolio in thirty days. Goldbaker-Reinz representatives offered no explanation for this extraordinary measure, and became incommunicado on the day the deadline fell. No contact could henceforth be made with the anomalous insurer. September 9 also saw a series of interdimensional peculiarities occur, including but not limited to:

* the failure of all thaumaturgical Ways linking baseline reality with the multiversal hub of the Wanderers' Library;
* the failure of [[[SCP-2264]]], preventing access to the Nevermeant and the City of Alagadda;
* loss of contact with Temporal Site-01, headquarters of the Temporal Anomalies Department;
* loss of contact with the Multi-Foundation Coalition;
* loss of contact with, and access to, all Exclusionary Sites.[[span class="fnnum"]].[[/span]][[span class="fncon"]]Exclusionary Sites exist outside of baseline reality and are designed to survive temporal or dimensional shifts.[[/span]]

It was presumed that baseline reality had sustained serious ontokinetic damage, severing it from the timeplane and all linked dimensions. The Departments of Ontokinetics and Temporal Affairs undertook priority one research on this subject, while a complete audit of Foundation operations was launched to determine the root cause. Though multiple facilities had reported containment failures or breaches on September 9, many precipitated by the multiversal shift, none appeared to carry causative potential. The only incident involving chronological material was a narrowly-averted cascade containment breach at Site-43 in Acroamatic Abatement Facility AAF-D, but that had taken place a full twenty-four hours earlier and was unlikely to be the culprit.

> **Dr. Ilse Reynders:** In retrospect, of course, we know it //was// the AAF-D breach which blew us past the pale and into the dark. But it didn't make sense back then, and it still doesn't make sense now. Why did it wait twenty-four hours? What kind of temporal anomaly recognizes and respects the human experience and partitioning of time? It was wholly unconnected to the actual period of the Earth's rotation, it was twenty-four hours to the precise second. Absurd.

On October 1, during Sunday mass, Saint Notre Dame Cathedral Basilica in Ottawa collapsed. Four thousand three hundred and eleven people were killed, officially. Unofficially, a further three hundred and eleven were crushed by masonry falling into Reliquary Area-27, located beneath the church. This was the headquarters of the Department of Tactical Theology, the entity responsible for planning the Foundation's response to deific threats. 

> **Dr. Brenda Corbin:** Though the Department had footholds at most major facilities, this disaster made the Theology and Teleology Section of Site-43 the foremost authority on religious counterwarfare. It would have been good to know that's what we were dealing with before we too became trapped, incommunicado, in a different subterranean structure.

> **Chief Delfina Ibanez:** Area-27 wasn't immediately deemed an attack on the Foundation. Separatist or anti-Catholic terrorist action was considered, and it was also possible that this had been either a random act of sabotage or the result of an intrinsic flaw in the basilica's architecture.

> **Chief Noè Nascimbeni:** Post-disaster investigations revealed inexplicable stressors on key load-bearing members, and general material failures which should have been impossible. By that time, however, the rest of the mess was well underway...

Ten days later the aging hulk of Site-246 on the floor of Lake Superior imploded, taking with it one hundred and nine staff members. This facility was so far past its prime that a collapse under any other circumstances would not have been suspicious; the Foundation only maintained it because the cost of reconstructing it should it again become needed would be far in excess of the cost of keeping it mostly intact. Nevertheless, the loss of two facilities in as many weeks was an immediate red flag, and the Foundation was put on provisional alert.

That same day, a tall and rangy woman wrapped in a grey shawl, a few scraps of messy copper hair streaming out around a wan and unsmiling face, walked barefoot down Bristol Beach Park on the Lake Superior shoreline. An amateur photographer took a snapshot of her standing there, looking pensively out over the water. The image was striking enough to win a photography contest a week later, perhaps the last photography contest ever held on the planet Earth.

> **Chief Delfina Ibanez:** And that's how the Foundation first started figuring it out. The figure was positively identified as Janet Gwilherm by artwork specialists at Site-28 scanning for anartists operating in public, and it became clear this was no coincidence. 

> **Dr. Allan McInnis:** With the benefit of hindsight, it's quite clear why she attended mass at Area-27 to inaugurate her campaign. Tactical Theology killed gods, and she believed herself to be one.

> **Dr. Brenda Corbin:** Functionally, she was.

> **Dr. Allan McInnis:** It is an unhelpful thought, but a persistent one nevertheless: if only we'd known where this was headed, sorrow and strife beyond measure could have been averted.
[[/div]]

