+ ##990011|2003##

++ 9 September
[[span style="font-family: BauhausLTDemi; font-size: 120%;"]]**[http://www.scpwiki.com/secure-facility-dossier-site-43 Site-43]: Lambton County, Ontario, Canada**[[/span]]
[[/=]]

----

//...where am I going?//

Allan McInnis lived by a schedule. He required seven hours of sleep each night, because Site-43 required focus and alertness from its Director. He required two hours of downtime, because most people required eight hours of sleep and at least one hour of recreation, and if it didn't look like he was getting that, some of his people might be guilted into foregoing what they desperately needed, and //he// needed them happy and healthy as possible. So at this point in his schedule, around six thirty in the afternoon, he would usually be checking with Operations Control to make sure nothing required his attention -- though he'd be paged if anything came up, that seven hour repose would be unattainable without peace of mind -- then make his way to his quarters for a simple dinner alone and an easy drift into dreamless slumber.

Even his deviations from schedule, to frustrate assassination attempts per directives from O5 Command, were scheduled. He kept the algorithm private, in case the attempts came //from// O5 Command.

Today, however, he was breaking with pattern. He'd stopped to visit his cabal of VIP actors in the breach of 2002, discussed the day's resurrections, their possible implications and the inexplicable second coming of the AAF-D disaster. Inappropriate though it was, he'd come to value the input of this unofficial inner circle on the shared central mystery of their lives. He'd made that deviation in sound mind. What happened next, however...

He had walked to the southern dorms when he should have been heading for the Director's Complex. Something in the back of his brain was pushing him that way; something was tugging at his nerve endings, making him move just //so.// He allowed it, because he knew that if the impetus originated outside of himself, he had means of arresting the process. But more than that, he was trained to recognize the signs of brainwashing or mind control -- even in himself, even in the moment of being compromised. He didn't think this was that. This was intuition, a burning certainty that he needed to be past the secondary cafeteria and standing in the southernmost janitorial service room by the time the clock struck--

//6:28?//

He stared at his watch as he entered the glorified closet, and wondered for a moment whether someone had managed to assassinate him after all. Was he deliriously running the rails of his immaculately-structured life in his mind while his body bled out on the tiles? Or was he a dead man walking, all countermeasures failed, his thoughts despite everything no longer his own?

Or had someone managed to conceptually poison the face of his watch? Because the instant the hour registered, he was suddenly struck by a sick headache.

And then, he wasn't.

"Ah." He nodded. "We've caught up."

Earlier that day he'd engaged in consultation with Thaddeus Xyank, head of the Temporal Anomalies Department. Xyank had been very interested in the story of the seven resurrected breach victims and the diverging timeline they claimed to have inhabited, the year they had lived which had never occurred. He had considered the risk of a temporal rubberband -- baseline reality cohering with this alternate sequence of events -- exceedingly low. If it was going to happen, it would have happened when the dead first walked again. It certainly wouldn't happen hours later.

It had, apparently, happened twenty-four hours later on the dot.

He wasn't standing in the closet anymore.

He was standing behind it.

[[div class="muddle"]]
Site cartography is a thankless chore.

Nobody really expects the official floorplans to bear anything but marginal relation to reality. The Foundation is so secretive that even its secrets have secrets, so anything purporting to outline the contours of a research and containment facility is bound to be lacking in salient details somewhere, perhaps even throughout. Nowhere is this more obvious than in depictions of the Director's Complex, a feature of most larger Sites. The person of the Site Director is surrounded by more security measures than anyone outside of the O5 Council and a few select Department heads, and their living and working spaces are an excellent example of this. It's not abnormal for the rough physical location to be known; for example, at Site-43, everyone knows that Director McInnis lives in a block of rooms in the northwest corner of Habitation and Sustenance. It //is// abnormal for anyone who isn't the Site Director to see the inside of their Complex. Vivian Scout, McInnis' predecessor, kept special rooms for his research partner Wynn Rydderech; Edwin Falkirk, in his extraordinarily short term as Director //pro tem// in January 2003, delighted in showing Section Chairs and Chief around the ordinarily off-limits space. But under McInnis, only situational access is allowed, and only for a vanishingly tiny subset of Site staff. His personal secretary, Zulfikar Alomerović, has the run of the outermost rooms. The All-Sections Chief, who fulfills the duties of Deputy Director, has a standing invitation to enter all but the inmost ones. But only McInnis really knows the state of his entire suite, which results in an interesting quirk not often discussed: the Director of Site-43 absolutely, definitely cleans his own washroom, and makes his own bed. There are also spaces beyond his private quarters to which he has access, of which only the Chiefs of the Janitorial and Maintenance and Security and Containment Sections are otherwise aware. There may even be hardened, maintenance-free areas only McInnis himself knows about. 

It's not impossible that some rooms are only known to the O5 Council. Once you start compartmentalizing, it's difficult to know where to stop.

[[>]]
-- Blank, //Lines in a Muddle//
[[/>]]
[[/div]]

He had often speculated as to the precise location of his bolthole.

His real bolthole, that was. He knew about the official one, the one his most senior Chairs and Chiefs were cleared to know about. It was accessible through the panel directly behind his desk in Admin and Oversight, which slid aside, framed painting and all, to allow access to a narrow passageway leading to a comfortable steel bunker with an ensuite washroom and enough supplies to outlast a brief siege. There was a weapons locker, a set of comfortable cots -- he was discouraged from bringing anyone else in with him, particularly since they would subsequently require amnesticization, but contingency plans are by their nature meant to be absent of unnecessarily strict particularities -- and untraceable terminal access to both 43NET and the Foundation-wide SCiPnet systems. This was where S&C would look for him, once the shit had stopped hitting the fan and the fan had been stopped and the shit had been mostly cleaned up, in a typical emergency situation. (The existence of 'typical emergency situations' was a sad fact of life at any facility doing containment duty.)

Anyone looking for him there today would be in for a series of incredibly nasty surprises which they would not have long to lament.

In cases where long-term severance of the Site's chief operating officer from its physical plant was required -- something which had happened but once during McInnis' tenure -- his personal data assistant would be pinged by a single message encrypted in such a way as to only be readable by the Director himself, inducing immediate cardiac arrest in anyone else witnessing it even briefly. The message would come directly from the chambers of the O5 Council at Site-01, and it would carry instructions for accessing the safest of all safe spaces at 43. He had no idea where these rooms were located or how to access them; he had been instructed to enter them once, years ago, and had pointedly disobeyed the order.

He had not, apparently, done so this time.

A figure appeared in the passage ahead, furtive, afraid, arm outstretched. McInnis braced himself for the impact of a bullet. He recognized a firing stance when he saw one.

And then his assistant rushed out to him, terror plastered across his young face. "What's wrong, sir?!" Zulfikar visibly restrained himself from grabbing his employer. "What are you doing out here?!"

"I'm afraid I couldn't tell you," McInnis sighed. "Perhaps you can tell me?"

