[[div class="lines"]]
Upon discovery of the Duluth photograph, Area-08 retasked the Foundation's satellites to locate Janet Gwilherm. She was located three days later on Interstate 29 in South Dakota, just outside Sioux Falls. It should have taken her three times as long to reach that point in her journey, though she didn't seem to be in any sort of hurry. While Foundation Mission Control started taking snapshots, Gwilherm glanced up into the eyes in the sky. They immediately went dark. Telemetry from ground-based telescopes revealed catastrophic system-wide atmospheric breakup, leading potentially to a Kessler effect in Earth orbit and immediately halving the Foundation's global communications capability.

> **Dr. Brenda Corbin:** She never displayed this level of long-distance dissolution again. At the moment it happened, Stewart Radcliffe was ranting on the Site-43 public address system about how his lover's reach was unconstrained by the slippery grasp of gravity. "The stars themselves are no object," I remember him saying. "She could reach up and pluck them down, if she took a notion." Thought it was just romantic nonsense at the time.

Gwilherm's journey west was almost entirely uneventful until the halfway point, when she paid a visit to Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming. This was no mere tourist stop, though she did visit the world-famous Old Faithful geyser long enough to force it to erupt at many times its usual force, resulting in the scalding deaths of several hundred visitors topside and a sizable number of SCP Foundation personnel belowground. Infrared surveillance performed after the fact revealed Gwilherm approaching an unremarkable park ranger station in the midst of the eruptions, effortlessly erasing its security countermeasures, and becoming the first person ever to force entry into [[[https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/scp-2000|Site-θ]]]. This was apparently a nominal, symbolic act, as she did not descend to the lower levels but instead left the park on U.S. Route 20 heading west. Site-θ was declared lost, all personnel either scalded to death or crushed when the rock and soil above became oversaturated with water. All assets within were presumably destroyed.

> **Dr. Allan McInnis:** There is little point in obfuscating the purpose of Site-θ now. It was used by my predecessors as a kind of 'reset button' for unmanageable XK-class crisis events. Had the connection been made sooner, it might have been more readily apparent that Agent Gwilherm was planning to enact a scheme of such staggering, devastating scope that she expected we would attempt to reboot human civilization to revert it.

The freak eruption was not immediately identified as an anomalous event, and while meteorological studies continued Gwilherm progressed through Idaho and Nevada without making any further stops, reaching California faster than a commercial airliner would have. She proceeded to the City of Sacramento, where she was to inaugurate her plan in earnest beyond simple spot treatments. She approached the perimeter of Technical Site-14 and instigated a security equipment failure at a distance, allowing a small group of previously unknown associates to enter in her stead. These arrived via Sea King helicopters belonging to MTF Epsilon-43 ("Day Trippers"), modified for long-distance travel, and transmitted valid Foundation identification codes. Among those debarking was Dr. Bernabé Del Olmo, Chair of Memetics and Countermemetics at Site-43. Within an hour, the Foundation's primary telecommunications hub in North America was under Gwilherm's control. No warning signals were sent during the initial occupation. Site-to-Site communications in California were disrupted at the moment Gwilherm arrived in the Santa Clara Valley, performing the same actions at Technical Site-15 with the same disastrous results. With the core staff of the Artificial Intelligence Applications Division under memetic control, Gwilherm now essentially owned SCiPnet and possessed the ability to reprogram all helper AIs for her own purposes. Still, these acts were not made immediately visible to the Foundation at large.

> **Dr. Eileen Veiksaar:** Smart. So very, very smart. She walked across the entire continent before showing her hand, because she knew that with 14 and 15 under her thumb we'd essentially already lost. Control the technology, control the game. It's what I would have done if I'd wanted to plot out the death of the Foundation.
[[/div]]

