[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

Zulfikar led him through the entrance to the bolthole proper, as they were standing in what amounted to its antechamber. He turned to the right wall and began patting it rhythmically, as though searching for a hidden panel or testing for hollowness. There was a rhythm to the taps, not precisely jaunty, but definitely familiar. Some of the taps went high up, nearly at the ceiling, and a few were down low, at about knee-level. 

McInnis snapped his mental fingers. He had a good ear for music, and knew this one well. Zulfikar was tapping out the lyrical beats to "I'm Still Standing" by Elton John. He, McInnis, had that song on his PDA. 

Zulfikar was the kind of person who listened to atmospheric sounds to relax. He didn't know much of anything about music, and didn't care to. He was, however, required to know what sort of music the Director listened to, since he could be called upon at any moment to confirm or deny the identity of someone claiming to //be// the Director. Still, he was tapping the song out like he really knew--

There was a soft //click,// and Zulfikar pushed the wall panel with both hands, and it sucked in then slid aside on silent, well-greased runners. This, then, was the entrance to the rest of the bunker.

Zulfikar didn't say anything until the panel was shut behind them again. McInnis watched closely, but wasn't able to discern how the young man had managed to make that happen. "Can I ask what you were doing out there, sir?"

McInnis shook his head. "Momentary disorientation. I'm sorry to make you worry."

One of the cardinal rules of timeline travel was not to tell anyone you were a timeline traveller. They never reacted well to that information, for a whole raft of reasons. If they didn't believe you, that was bad. If they did, it could be much, much worse.

"You haven't stepped out there since we first came in. Are you alright? Running a fever or anything?" The secretary looked concerned, but not suspicious. Good.

McInnis shook his head. "I feel fine." He //did// feel fine. He felt well-rested and alert, well-fed and clean. He wasn't wearing the same work shirt and pair of pants he'd been wearing just a few minutes ago, but what he was wearing was roughly equivalent; the cut was a little off, the shirt a little baggy, and that all tracked, since someone had obviously stocked the bunker with clothes similar to the ones he owned without having direct access to his wardrobe. Pinching his actual clothes to prepare him for the apocalypse was too Byzantine for even the O5 Council. "It was a momentary thing. I suppose I needed some fresh air."

Zulfikar sighed. "Sir, you know we're in here for a reason. We need to keep the continuity. We're the only ones fully unaffected."

That didn't sound good. McInnis decided to pry, by means of pretending not to. "Mm. I have my doubts on that score."

The other man gave him a funny look, then slipped past to lead him along the narrow passage. It was twin to any number of Level 3+ escape tunnels crisscrossing the bedrock between each Section of the Site. "I know they're not all lost, sir, but they can't have spent that much time in the company of lunatics without suffering some memetic effect."

The general trend seemed to be suggesting there were live staff at Site-43, divided in some proportion between trustworthy and untrustworthy. So, not //quite// an apocalypse, then. It was a start. "What would you estimate the numbers are? If I asked you to guess, based on only what you personally are aware of."

His assistant's eyes rolled back as he engaged in a little mental math. "We started with, what, six hundred and forty-one people? Not counting the refugees, who..." He winced. "Who don't count for much now anyway, so we'll leave them out of this. About half of those are dead now, so..."

Eileen Veiksaar had once referred to McInnis' facial expressions and body language as, collectively, his 'firewall'. What he was really thinking and feeling didn't show unless he decided to make an exception. There was no outward indication, not that the man walking ahead of him would have seen it anyway, of the effect this casual writing off of over three hundred staff members and untold numbers of civilians had on his equanimity.

"...with about two hundred confirmed losses to Mukami, which may be unrecoverable, there should still be over a hundred people still active and theoretically aligned with the Principles." //Secure, Contain, Protect.// "But this whole Site is a mess of memetics and mind control and such, not to mention all the unabated material seeping through everywhere, so I'd be hard pressed to trust anyone still working here."

//So, a __near__-apocalypse, then.// This was, to put it lightly, disheartening. McInnis had Level 5 clearance, absurdly high, one full point over most of his peers in the Site Director cohort, and that entitled him to know a few things about how the Foundation handled alternate timelines. The unofficial motto of the Temporal Anomalies Department, "Stop Changing the Past," pretty much summed it all up. If the timeline split, well, that was tough potatoes. Going back in time to set right what once went wrong carried far too high a risk of setting it far wronger, not least because the vagaries of cause and effect were complicated enough that even a stochastic supercomputer was unlikely to be able to figure out the precise combination of actions required to revert things back to baseline -- assuming baseline's criteria could be fully outlined in a world where they had never existed, and assuming human beings could then execute the necessary courses of action to a tee.

In other words, all of those dead people were going to remain dead.

The tunnel was long, and a bit of mental mapping suggested his bunker was ensconced in a bedrock shell between H&S, I&T, and R&E. That made sense, had in fact been what he'd already suspected beforehand, since that chunk of unused real estate was especially chunky. The distant lights they were approaching suggested he had time for at least one more pertinent question. He chose and crafted it very, very carefully. His first draft asked after the fates of the Chairs and Chiefs, but they could very well all have been taken out in one cataclysmic strike, and then Zulfikar would suspect him for being an impostor for not knowing that.

"At last count," he said slowly, "who were the highest-ranking survivors?"

Zulfikar glanced back at him curiously. "You planning something, sir?" He looked back at the light, shaking off his moment of mild insubordination to come up with the appropriate response. "Zlatá and Msuya are dead. Du, Bremmel, and LeClair are missing, Van Rompay, Anoki, Styles, Mataxas and Skellicorne are all turned. So in order of hierarchical seniority, they're still working with: Blank, Ibanez, Nascimbeni, and Veiksaar. Oh, uh, the Director too, I suppose." He shook his head, as though there were something troubling about that final item.

McInnis certainly found it troubling.

//I'm not the Director.//

It was in unhappy and confused possession of this knowledge that he walked into the hiding place reserved for the Director-in-self-imposed-exile of Site-43.

The bunker was considerably more spacious than the bolthole, though obviously not a patch on the extensive Director's Complex; certain rooms in the latter had gone unused since the mid-1960s. The central space was a comfortable lounge with a pair of vinyl couches and one vinyl chair, all in black. The floor was whitewashed wood, as were the wall panels, which ended halfway up to reveal the concrete slabs beneath. There was a refrigerator, a bookshelf full of books -- McInnis noted copies of most of his favourites, and a large selection of reading material useful to a man running a small war from well behind the front lines. Tactical manuals. Protocol overviews. Threat assessments. All of it with large print on the black bindings, for quick and easy reference. There was a television screen on one wall, hooked up to a placidly blinking modem on a black metal shelf bolted beside it. There were two desks, one large and set back from the wall, one small and pushed up against it. The former was spotless; the latter was plastered with papers. There were doors at each cardinal compass point, leading no doubt to private rooms and even-more-private bathrooms, as well as a library, a server room, and undoubtedly a secure communications station. This wasn't really supposition; Foundation security protocol wasn't hard to judge when you'd worked there for nearly three decades.

"Overwatch wants to talk to you." Zulfikar wouldn't make eye contact now, instead walking over to his desk to straighten out the piles of paper.

McInnis nodded at his assistant's back. "You told them you couldn't find me."

To his credit, the young man turned around and returned the nod. "Yes, sir. I'm under orders."

"As am I," //no doubt,// "of course." McInnis paused. He had another thorny question; he wasn't actually sure which room contained the terminal he wanted, and wasn't precisely sure how to ask. If he walked into Zulfikar's room instead, well, the game might very well be up. His assistant was quick on the uptake. He had to be.

As it always did, the solution presented itself elegantly after a few moments' pondering. He walked to the refrigerator, opened it up, and examined the contents carefully before selecting a can of generic soda pop. He closed the door, pulled the tab, and took a sip.

Over the edge of the can, he saw Zulfikar's eyes flicker. Zulfikar didn't see him see it.

McInnis finished his gulp, pulled a handkerchief out of his pocket to dab delicately at his lips, then nodded again. "Very well. I shall phone home. Try to relax, please, Zulfikar."

He walked casually to the door his assistant's eyes had gone to, in his anxiety over the Director's pointed refusal to make the call with alacrity. He was pleased and relieved to recognize one of his suits on the bed within, neatly-pressed and ready for the next day's whatever, and the keycard-locked door leading inevitably to his secure communications channel. Almost as an afterthought, he reached into his vest and produced the piece of paper he knew would be there, glanced at it for confirmation, and nodded.

It was time to find out what was what.

