[[div class="lines"]]
The first undeniable evidence of a wider pattern came when Gwilherm trekked across the state of Nevada to attack Armed Biological Containment Area-14. This was the headquarters of MTF Nu-7 ("Hammer Down"), first responders in the event that another facility went rogue or went dark. This time she did something that couldn't be brushed under the carpet, either by her or us: she brought the Ruby Mountains down, killing the entire battalion without a single shot fired.

Area-14 was under minute-by-minute scrutiny, as one of the most vital elements in the Foundation's disaster response plan, and its destruction immediately triggered a declaration from Overwatch Command that a state of internal emergency now existed. The O5 Council attempted to issue a general call to arms from Site-01, but were unable to do so as a massive wave of cyberattacks originating at Site-15 overwhelmed the information technology staff at every loyal facility. Artificially Intelligent Conscripts reprogrammed with malicious code by the AIAD invaded each server, took control of the local systems and began wreaking havoc. Research and Containment Site-56 in the Black Rock Desert of Nevada, the largest and most vital containment facility in the American West, immediately failed as its staff had already been engaged in a losing battle to control the variety of spatial and humanoid anomalies under its care. The desert promptly became a topological nightmare looping into, around and over itself, resulting in the loss of two commercial airliners and the entirety of the City of Reno. Research and Development Site-78 in Chugwater, Wyoming was destroyed by the Serpent's Hand after a raid to acquire their anomalous library; a missive from the Wanderers' Library addressed to the O5 Council apologized for the attack, explaining that it had been triggered by the failure of Site-78's internal network as "some knowledge is too dangerous to be lost." The nuclear warheads at Research and Containment Site-23, Research and Containment Site-64, and Containment Area-25 immediately activated, with a civilian death toll estimated in the hundreds of thousands. The United States federal government immediately assumed it had been attacked in a first strike by a rival nuclear power, as there had been detonations on both the eastern and western seaboard and the entirety of Portland, Oregon had been lost along with Site-64, and scrambled to find a likely culprit for reprisal. A general collapse of intercontinental relations, both governmental and intra-Foundation, quickly ensued; the progression of Gwilherm's campaign overseas by proxy will be addressed separately rather than concurrently, to avoid further confusing an already overcomplicated narrative.

There was an odd blip in the narrative as Gwilherm headed back east. As she approached Site-41 in Central Colorado, Central Colorado disappeared.

> **Dr. Lillian Lillihammer:** I have my theories, but I'll have to wait and see if they pop back into existence to ask them if I'm right.

Undeterred, Gwilherm proceeded to Cyberanomalous Containment and Research Site-119 in Mound City, Kansas, an AIAD startup facility developing artificial reality projects which had become the //de facto// headquarters for resisting attacks from Site-15. It was expected that she would simply level the structure, already possessing a dedicated IT crowd in California, but she instead brought down the outer walls so that an attacking force could swarm in and prepare the personnel for conversion by Del Olmo.

> **Dr. Eileen Veiksaar:** The European networks were particularly well-hardened against cyberattacks, and possessed electronic redoubts her AIAD folks couldn't get at. This was presumably an attempt to recruit enough extra programmers and acquire enough extra hardware to overwhelm the folks overseas via sheer force.

The next target seemed obvious: Site-184, one of the Foundation's main North Atlantic seaports. It was expected that Gwilherm would arrive, the Site would collapse into a pile of rubble, and its vengeful Mobile Task Forces would move rapidly to contain her. This was not what happened. Gwilherm's arrival caused MTF helicopters to fall from the sky, wheels to fall off armoured personnel carriers, bunkers and foxholes to seal themselves up, but the Site personnel were not killed as they had been at her previous stopping points. Site-184 became a makeshift holding facility for everyone who worked there: the doors and door locks fused, the elevators ceased to function, and every means of escape or egress was blocked. No casualties were immediately reported, save for the occupants of the more dramatically-trashed vehicles. It wouldn't be for several weeks that we discovered why. In the meantime, supplies would last. The staff of Site-184 had some time to enjoy their curious mercy.

Six days later, as fully expected, Gwilherm arrived at Site-55. She found it largely undefended; the Overseer Council had decreed that only facilities with alpha-one priority would be defended, and so the task forces from 55 had been redirected to Site-19. The cutting of losses had begun. Key members of the Group of Interest research division were relocated to Site-19, along with most of their protectors, while Gwilherm ground their former home to dust. 

> **Chief Delfina Ibanez:** Keeping the GoI experts was an act of desperation. Overwatch clearly hoped that whoever this bitch was, she was working for someone they already knew about, or could learn about fast. What they didn't know, however, wasn't what was going to hurt them.

What followed was a flurry of activity, as this portion of the Eastern Seaboard was lousy with Sites and Areas. Gwilherm stomped Site-28 in SoHo without breaking a sweat, but left its collection of anomalous art curiously untouched. She performed similar acts at Site-58 in Nanticoke, Pennsylvania, though the results were markedly different. At Site-28, just about everyone she freed was happy to go rampaging through New York. At 58, she couldn't even goad the animals into attacking their former handlers. As at 43, that facility's staff had pursued more humane containment methods as a programmatic experiment, and the results were plain to see. There were escapees, of course, and damage was done, but on the whole the scene remained more calm and orderly.

This state of affairs would not, however, last. On the day Gwilherm walked out of 58, leaving barrackses full of guards with jammed guns and tasers with dead batteries and keycards that could unlock, but could not lock, their doors, the first wave of her followers broke on the Nova Scotian shore. The modified long-distance Chinook helicopters once utilized by MTF Pi-43 ("Garbage In, Garbage Out") to transport anomalies and VIPs to and from Lake Huron arrived at Site-184 carrying a dark woman dressed in bright colours, flashing a bright smile and interacting eagerly with each individual 'rescued' from the rubble. These were the first converts to the cult of Ana Mukami outside of Site-43, and they would proceed in Gwilherm's wake in the days to come, turning Foundation employees and recalcitrant anomalies to their singular cause. Mukami continued on to 28 and 58 as well; her work apparently able to take care of itself from that point onward, she flew back home and left her underlings to carry on.

> **Chief Delfina Ibanez:** If you ask me, Gwilherm and Mukami didn't like working together. Those seven freaks had a lot in common, but familiarity seemed to breed a whole hell of a lot more than just contempt between them.

So it was that when Gwilherm arrived at the outskirts of Site-19's interdiction zone in Pennsylvania, she had an army with her. They had already despoiled the three major facilities within the city of Philadelphia: breaking down the Foundation's primary containment R&D projects at Site-98, converting the humanoid anomalies integrated into the Foundation's command structure at Site-322, and arming themselves with a variety of anomalous tools from Area-179. For the first time in its history, the largest research and containment facility on the globe, the centre of the Foundation's operations, was under credible threat of destruction from a hostile Group of Interest.

Dr. Jay Everwood of the GoI research group, formerly based in Site-55, proposed a radical solution. Gwilherm's activities were obviously targeted against systems of control, order, and most of all, containment. The majority of the hostile and neutral organizations against which the Foundation regularly acted were opposed to at least one of those principles. They might, in a pinch such as this, provide willing and useful allies. The request was forwarded on to Site-01.

The O5 Council unanimously rejected it.
[[/div]]

