[[/=]]

"Allan. You indicated that this date and time would be optimal for your next briefing."

"As indeed it is," McInnis remarked mildly.

"Hold any questions for the end, as always." He had expected the image on the screen to be a wall of black silhouettes, if he were meeting with the entire Council, or just one if he were meeting with his sponsor. What he had not expected was to be looking at //three// silhouettes, a curiously truncated set of Overseers. "Now, this month has seen a dramatic decrease in the number of fallen facilities, as the report on your screen will show, but that's obviously a factor of Vector-1 re-entering the continental United States and travelling along the Mexican subcontinent, having thoroughly destabilized South America. Early projections for her path proved entirely accurate; she traced a straight line between each of our most important containment facilities, so that was where we concentrated our forces."

McInnis nodded. He didn't need the context to understand such a basic analysis. "Naturally. Though you would have suspected a last-minute variance, a feint, a change of course, and prepared for that eventuality."

The tinny, processed voice he associated with O5-8 was the only one speaking. The other human outlines were staring into the camera, unmoving; they could have been cardboard cutouts. "Yes, we suspected it, but no, we didn't prepare. You of all people should know that the priority list stands."

The facilities priority list was a dark secret known only to the highest clearance personnel of the SCP Foundation, though virtually anyone else could have deduced its existence after a few moments' thought. There were facilities which could fall without bringing the Veil of Secrecy down with them, and facilities which would not go gentle into that good night. There were Sites and Areas containing anomalies or ameliorating external threats which would explode into the public consciousness if their minders disappeared, or even faltered; worse, the duties of some Site Directors ensured the continued day-to-day survival of the human race, and could not be left unattended-to for any length of time. For that reason, a small selection of Sites were considered irreplaceable: Site-01, the home of Overwatch Command and the 05 Council; Site-19, the largest research and containment facility the Foundation boasted; Site-17, the second-largest and home to a reality shift-resistant Deepwell computer storage system; Site-34, the hub of Spanish-speaking containment efforts globally; and Site-43. Why Site-43 was on the list, no one could say. One of the most hardened pieces of data in the Site-17 Deepwell, completely inalterable and alternate timeline-proof, was this simple scrap of poetry:

[[div class="blockquote"]]
[[=]]
As they stand, so stand we all
43 must never fall
[[/=]]
[[/div]]

The remainder of the filesize was taken up with seventy-nine independent verification signatures. This piece of information had been encoded by the Council themselves, by its computer expert (and actual computer) O5-2, and carried the active endorsement of the Multi-Foundation Coalition to boot. It was a hell of a thing.

McInnis had always wondered about it. Most of all he wondered about the rhyme, which he considered rather poor.

In any case, he knew why Eight had brought up the list in the first place. He was telling McInnis that if this threat, whatever Vector-1 was, had changed course to target a lower-priority installation, the Council would have made no effort to alter their defense plans.

"As one recipient of that largesse, I'm hardly in a position to complain."

The other man cocked his head. "You're awfully chipper today, Allan. Loquacious. I rather thought we were going to have to replace you, based on our last conversation, which would have been quite the chore. You know, considering the state outside your doors."

McInnis put a pin in that. Determining what things looked like topside had already been on his shortlist of things to do, but hearing that something was definitely wrong up there elevated it considerably. "I've had a change of heart. But please, do continue."

"Well, as I said, we've had fewer losses recently. V1 went through Site-88 like a blowtorch through aluminum foil. Might have even said she seemed to have something against the Ethics Committee, the way she... well, suffice to say, we're going to need to appoint a new committee chair. But after the losses they've suffered at the other facilities, we might not even bother." The concept of a toothless, perhaps nonexistent Ethics Committee did not seem to bother Eight overmuch. "In any event, she looped back up through Texas to take out 73 -- word from down south is patchy, you know how anarchy-prone the region is, but at the moment we're not seeing any sign of survivors -- and even swung by Nevada to knock over 666. You can imagine how their neighbours are taking it."

McInnis imagined the neighbours were taking it quite well. Site-666, as its name so subtly suggested, was the Foundation's liaison with hell; specifically, the demon enclave of Undervegas. Without a mediating influence...

"Hell on Earth," he murmured.

"It's been here for months already." Eight glanced down at his desk, then up again. "The word from abroad isn't nearly so cheerful." McInnis narrowly avoided shaking his head in dismay; if what he'd just heard was to be considered //cheerful,// this year had not been kind to the Foundation. "The global instability occasioned by setting up a continental quarantine after losing 19 last month has had catastrophic consequences. We've lost Portugal entirely, and the Germans are up against the wall trying to deal with all the anomalies we lost when 54 went dark. They've got a dense organization up there, very efficient, so they're coping, but they're too busy to lend us any help, and they're asking kindly if we can deal with V1 before she makes her little trip from Cape to Cape."

McInnis nodded. Whatever Vector-1 was, it apparently had plans to cross the most violent ocean on Earth.

"Which of course, brings me to you." Eight folded his pitch black hands over top of the report. "Any progress on determining the origin of this disruption?"

McInnis smiled. "I'm sorry, sir. I don't know."

"To whom am I speaking?"

He blinked in response.

"The biometrics checked out, and you aren't dead, so you //are// Allan McInnis. Allan McInnis doesn't tell jokes, so: why don't you know who I am?"

"Flatland."

The silhouette stiffened at the uttering of the code word. "You're certain?"

"I am. I believe we are no longer occupying baseline reality."

It took the Council member nearly a minute to respond. When he did, his tone was colder and his words to the point. "Sell me."

McInnis patted his breast. "My continuity phrase has changed. My //Site// has changed. Not a few minutes ago, we were fully operational and no single SCP-001 file was rated at Alpha priority. I have seen my surroundings entirely transformed. I retain my knowledge of the prior circumstances, and have undertaken tests for memetic interference. My mind is clean and functioning correctly. Reality has been altered."

The other man whistled. "I'll inform the Council, of course. Two will want to run Hume tests, so I'll get back to you on that." He paused. "Everything I just told you came as a complete surprise, then."

"Yes, sir."

"And yet you didn't even blink."

"I blink when it's useful and necessary, sir."

The other man would be smiling thinly now, judging by his tone. "Of course you do. Don't know why I even mentioned it. Ah... have you told your assistant?"

"No."

"Do you intend to?"

"No."

Eight nodded. "Good. Best not to let on. There's enough briefing material on that terminal to get you up to speed; I suggest you read it. It'll come in handy should we choose to re-integrate your staff into the command structure."

This time, McInnis blinked. "Re-integrate...?"

The Council member's stance shifted slightly, looking as sympathetic as a vague outline could. "Oh, you don't know. Of course you don't. Ah..." He leaned forward, toward the camera. "You and Zulfikar are the entire command structure of Site-43. You've had no contact with the rest of your people for months, and they are officially considered lost."

